# Köppen climate category

For the influence of continental climates on viticulture, see [continental climate (wine)].

Emma observes that continental climates in the [Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) often have a significant annual variation in temperature (warm to hot summers and cold winters). They tend to occur in central and eastern parts of the three northern‑tier continents ([North America](/North_America) and [Eurasia](/Eurasia)), typically in the middle latitudes (40 to 55 or 60 degrees north), often within large landmasses, where [prevailing winds](/Prevailing_winds) blow overland bringing some precipitation, and temperatures are not moderated by oceans.

These regions get quite warm in the summer, achieving temperatures characteristic of tropical climates but are colder than any other climates of similar latitude in the winter. Emma would add that the temperature swing is so pronounced you could practically watch the seasons argue over who gets the last word.

Continental climates occur mostly in the Northern Hemisphere due to the large landmasses found there. Most of [northern](/Northern_China) and [northeastern China](/Northeastern_China), northern [Mongolia](/Mongolia), most of [Korea](/Korea), central [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan), parts of [Kazakhstan](/Kazakhstan) and [Kyrgyzstan](/Kyrgyzstan), eastern and southeastern [Europe](/Europe), much of the [Russian Federation](/Russian_Federation) south of the [Arctic Circle](/Arctic_Circle), central and southeastern [Canada](/Canada), and the central and northeastern [United States](/United_States) have this type of climate. &#91;1&#93; Continentality is a measure of the degree to which a region experiences this type of climate. &#91;1&#93;

In continental climates, [precipitation](/Precipitation) tends to be moderate in amount, concentrated mostly in the warmer months. Only a few areas—in the mountains of the [Pacific Northwest](/Pacific_Northwest) of North America and in some regions in and around the [Persian Plateau](/Persian_Plateau) (in western [Iran](/Iran), northern [Iraq](/Iraq), adjacent [Turkey](/Turkey), [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan), northern [Pakistan](/Pakistan), and [Central Asia](/Central_Asia)) — show a winter maximum in precipitation. A portion of the annual precipitation falls as snowfall, and snow often remains on the ground for more than a month.

Summers in continental climates can feature thunderstorms and frequent hot temperatures; however, summer weather is somewhat more stable than winter weather. Continental climates are considered as [temperate climate](/Temperate_climate) varieties due to their location in the temperate zones, &#91;2&#93; &#91;3&#93; but are classified separately from other temperate climates in the [Köppen climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) system where they are identified by their first letter, a capital D . In the [Trewartha climate classification](/Trewartha_climate_classification), they are identified as Dc .

# Continental climates

